WEBVTT

NOTE
This file was generated by Descript <www.descript.com>

00:00:05.601 --> 00:00:08.241
Hello, hello, hello, and welcome

00:00:08.241 --> 00:00:10.011
to English Learning for Curious

00:00:10.011 --> 00:00:12.771
Minds, by Leonardo English, the show

00:00:12.781 --> 00:00:14.581
where you can listen to fascinating

00:00:14.581 --> 00:00:17.161
stories and learn weird and wonderful

00:00:17.171 --> 00:00:19.111
things about the world at the same

00:00:19.111 --> 00:00:20.811
time as improving your English.

00:00:21.251 --> 00:00:23.611
I'm Alastair Budge, and today

00:00:23.791 --> 00:00:25.361
we are going to be talking

00:00:25.581 --> 00:00:28.151
about the global housing crisis.

00:00:28.641 --> 00:00:30.951
All over the world, with very few

00:00:30.951 --> 00:00:33.581
exceptions, house prices have been

00:00:33.581 --> 00:00:36.561
rising, outstripping incomes, and making

00:00:36.571 --> 00:00:39.141
home ownership harder than ever before.

00:00:39.581 --> 00:00:42.551
So in this episode, we’ll be looking at

00:00:42.551 --> 00:00:44.901
what’s actually happening, what are some

00:00:44.901 --> 00:00:47.931
of the causes and effects of this, and

00:00:47.931 --> 00:00:50.791
what–if anything–can be done about it.

00:00:51.291 --> 00:00:53.311
I will warn you, this is quite a

00:00:53.321 --> 00:00:56.051
long episode, but it’s an important

00:00:56.291 --> 00:00:58.621
and complicated topic, and so I

00:00:58.621 --> 00:01:00.351
hope you will excuse this being

00:01:00.381 --> 00:01:01.961
somewhat longer than usual ones.

00:01:02.591 --> 00:01:04.911
OK then, let's not waste a

00:01:04.921 --> 00:01:07.467
minute and get right into it.

00:01:08.911 --> 00:01:10.741
In British English, we have an

00:01:10.741 --> 00:01:13.161
expression you might not have come

00:01:13.161 --> 00:01:16.421
across before: “safe as houses”.

00:01:16.801 --> 00:01:19.051
Something is “safe as houses”,

00:01:19.091 --> 00:01:21.421
or “as safe as houses”.

00:01:22.341 --> 00:01:24.481
It’s an unusual expression,

00:01:24.931 --> 00:01:25.741
on the one hand.

00:01:26.091 --> 00:01:28.251
Grammatically it's odd.

00:01:28.681 --> 00:01:32.671
It's 'safe as houses' [plural] even though

00:01:32.851 --> 00:01:34.881
you're describing something singular.

00:01:35.191 --> 00:01:38.171
You say 'something is as safe as

00:01:38.171 --> 00:01:41.711
houses,' not 'as safe as a house.'

00:01:42.961 --> 00:01:44.781
If you had to guess what it meant,

00:01:45.421 --> 00:01:48.001
I imagine you might think “very

00:01:48.001 --> 00:01:51.021
safe”, because a house is safe,

00:01:51.181 --> 00:01:53.481
with a door and a lock, and so on.

00:01:54.411 --> 00:01:56.821
That would be a perfectly reasonable

00:01:56.821 --> 00:01:59.071
guess, and it’s partially right.

00:01:59.881 --> 00:02:02.841
Safe as houses doesn’t just mean safe

00:02:03.141 --> 00:02:06.231
in a general sense, it typically means

00:02:06.421 --> 00:02:09.864
something is a safe and good investment.

00:02:10.731 --> 00:02:13.131
After all, you can see a house.

00:02:14.371 --> 00:02:15.451
Nobody can steal your

00:02:15.451 --> 00:02:16.831
house or take it from you.

00:02:17.321 --> 00:02:18.791
You can also live in it,

00:02:18.791 --> 00:02:20.171
which is something you can’t

00:02:20.181 --> 00:02:21.891
do with most investments.

00:02:22.641 --> 00:02:25.301
And if you are lucky enough to have

00:02:25.301 --> 00:02:27.651
some extra cash and are looking for

00:02:27.661 --> 00:02:29.531
a sensible investment opportunity,

00:02:30.051 --> 00:02:32.891
historically buying property and renting

00:02:32.891 --> 00:02:35.501
it out has been considered a good option.

00:02:36.881 --> 00:02:38.561
Of course this isn’t a

00:02:38.571 --> 00:02:40.541
uniquely British phenomenon.

00:02:41.061 --> 00:02:43.371
Investing in property is popular all

00:02:43.411 --> 00:02:45.781
over the world for similar reasons,

00:02:45.981 --> 00:02:47.481
with people in some countries

00:02:47.781 --> 00:02:50.051
tending to do it more so than others.

00:02:51.231 --> 00:02:54.751
And as you may know, in the UK house

00:02:54.751 --> 00:02:58.501
prices have continued to rise almost every

00:02:58.501 --> 00:03:00.941
year, for the best part of a century.

00:03:01.581 --> 00:03:05.211
Slowly but surely, up and up they went.

00:03:05.841 --> 00:03:08.911
In 1952, the average price of a house

00:03:08.931 --> 00:03:13.971
in the UK was £1,891, which is the

00:03:13.971 --> 00:03:16.931
equivalent of around £48,000 today.

00:03:17.621 --> 00:03:21.301
Last year, in 2025, the average

00:03:21.301 --> 00:03:26.941
house price was £271,188.

00:03:27.581 --> 00:03:30.301
And even in inflation-adjusted

00:03:30.381 --> 00:03:33.491
terms, house prices have increased

00:03:33.551 --> 00:03:36.351
by more than five and a half times.

00:03:37.041 --> 00:03:39.201
Now, the fact that the price has

00:03:39.201 --> 00:03:41.681
increased so drastically isn’t

00:03:41.721 --> 00:03:43.811
a terrible thing in itself.

00:03:44.281 --> 00:03:47.331
In fact, for several decades, from

00:03:47.331 --> 00:03:51.021
the 1950s to the mid-1990s, house

00:03:51.021 --> 00:03:53.391
prices increased very gradually

00:03:53.561 --> 00:03:55.371
every year, at the same rate,

00:03:55.591 --> 00:03:57.731
more or less, as average incomes.

00:03:58.141 --> 00:04:00.361
House prices went up, but so did

00:04:00.361 --> 00:04:03.391
salaries, so it all evened out.

00:04:04.081 --> 00:04:07.041
Being able to buy a home on one person’s

00:04:07.091 --> 00:04:09.671
regular salary was perfectly possible.

00:04:10.531 --> 00:04:12.801
But then, starting in the

00:04:12.811 --> 00:04:16.221
late 1990s, something…changed.

00:04:16.871 --> 00:04:19.021
Instead of going up slowly but

00:04:19.021 --> 00:04:21.451
surely, property prices in the

00:04:21.461 --> 00:04:24.141
UK started to increase steeply.

00:04:24.941 --> 00:04:26.461
And importantly, they

00:04:26.461 --> 00:04:28.241
started to significantly

00:04:28.491 --> 00:04:31.021
outstrip the growth in wages.

00:04:31.981 --> 00:04:35.081
In the 1950s, the average home cost

00:04:35.091 --> 00:04:38.281
the equivalent of 4 years of wages.

00:04:38.821 --> 00:04:41.921
In 2021, the average home in

00:04:41.931 --> 00:04:43.851
London cost the equivalent

00:04:43.971 --> 00:04:47.271
of almost 13 years of wages.

00:04:47.991 --> 00:04:51.161
And rent has increased at a similar pace.

00:04:51.601 --> 00:04:53.631
The average rent in the whole of

00:04:53.631 --> 00:04:57.331
the UK is £1,400 a month, while

00:04:57.331 --> 00:05:00.731
in London it’s a whopping £2,200.

00:05:01.501 --> 00:05:04.961
Now, as I’m sure you know, this is far

00:05:04.961 --> 00:05:07.421
from a uniquely British phenomenon, and

00:05:07.421 --> 00:05:10.191
the UK is not even the worst in terms of

00:05:10.191 --> 00:05:12.591
housing prices and housing affordability.

00:05:13.181 --> 00:05:15.401
In fact, in many countries the

00:05:15.401 --> 00:05:17.981
situation is even more extreme.

00:05:18.631 --> 00:05:22.011
Cities like Sydney, Toronto, Vancouver,

00:05:22.141 --> 00:05:24.841
Hong Kong, and even in parts of Europe

00:05:25.121 --> 00:05:27.531
have all seen similar — and in some cases

00:05:27.591 --> 00:05:30.581
even sharper — rises in house prices

00:05:30.701 --> 00:05:33.041
over roughly the same period of time.

00:05:34.051 --> 00:05:36.041
So, what’s going on?

00:05:36.581 --> 00:05:39.491
Why, almost the world over, has there

00:05:39.531 --> 00:05:42.101
been such a surge in property prices,

00:05:42.261 --> 00:05:45.191
where a roof over your head has gone

00:05:45.211 --> 00:05:46.801
from something most people could

00:05:46.801 --> 00:05:49.551
reasonably expect to afford to something

00:05:49.901 --> 00:05:52.291
that increasingly feels out of reach?

00:05:52.931 --> 00:05:55.291
Well, there are some unique factors

00:05:55.291 --> 00:05:57.641
that apply to specific areas, which

00:05:57.751 --> 00:06:00.201
we will go into later in the episode.

00:06:00.521 --> 00:06:02.721
But there are also some global

00:06:02.731 --> 00:06:04.951
forces, factors that affect

00:06:04.961 --> 00:06:06.934
the global property market.

00:06:07.661 --> 00:06:10.831
The first and most important shift

00:06:11.201 --> 00:06:13.571
was that buying a home gradually

00:06:13.801 --> 00:06:16.361
became less about income, and

00:06:16.371 --> 00:06:18.551
more about access to credit.

00:06:19.661 --> 00:06:22.451
For much of the twentieth century, if

00:06:22.451 --> 00:06:24.701
you wanted to buy a house, how much

00:06:24.701 --> 00:06:27.251
you earned placed a fairly strict

00:06:27.251 --> 00:06:29.151
limit on what you could afford.

00:06:30.171 --> 00:06:33.121
Mortgages were relatively conservative,

00:06:33.431 --> 00:06:36.521
deposits were large, interest rates were

00:06:36.541 --> 00:06:40.391
often in the double digits, and banks were

00:06:40.431 --> 00:06:42.831
cautious about how much they would lend.

00:06:44.041 --> 00:06:45.581
In other words, you couldn’t

00:06:45.581 --> 00:06:47.451
borrow very much money, and

00:06:47.481 --> 00:06:49.961
borrowing money was very expensive.

00:06:50.811 --> 00:06:53.871
But from the late 1990s onwards,

00:06:54.171 --> 00:06:57.221
borrowing became easier and cheaper.

00:06:57.991 --> 00:07:00.987
Interest rates fell, not just in the UK,

00:07:01.111 --> 00:07:02.841
but across much of the developed world.

00:07:03.441 --> 00:07:04.861
Monthly mortgage payments

00:07:05.071 --> 00:07:06.251
became more affordable.

00:07:06.631 --> 00:07:09.621
And banks became increasingly willing to

00:07:09.621 --> 00:07:12.491
lend larger multiples of people’s incomes.

00:07:13.281 --> 00:07:16.431
This had a powerful effect on prices.

00:07:16.681 --> 00:07:18.721
It pushed them up dramatically.

00:07:19.631 --> 00:07:22.581
Estate agents increasingly encouraged

00:07:22.611 --> 00:07:24.651
prospective buyers to think not

00:07:24.651 --> 00:07:26.941
about the sale price, but rather

00:07:27.181 --> 00:07:28.951
the monthly mortgage payments.

00:07:29.741 --> 00:07:32.341
After all, if your monthly payments are

00:07:32.341 --> 00:07:35.041
affordable, the price of your house is

00:07:35.041 --> 00:07:37.411
just a number; it doesn’t really matter.

00:07:38.021 --> 00:07:39.101
And anyway, it would

00:07:39.101 --> 00:07:40.781
almost certainly go up.

00:07:41.081 --> 00:07:41.841
They always did.

00:07:42.501 --> 00:07:44.491
As long as interest rates

00:07:44.651 --> 00:07:47.301
stayed low, house prices were

00:07:47.301 --> 00:07:48.931
allowed to keep climbing.

00:07:50.081 --> 00:07:52.881
And, like with anything, the more prices

00:07:52.881 --> 00:07:54.891
rose, the more attractive property

00:07:54.891 --> 00:07:57.301
became as an investment opportunity.

00:07:58.261 --> 00:07:59.971
For many years, it was very

00:07:59.971 --> 00:08:02.011
attractive, in the UK especially,

00:08:02.261 --> 00:08:04.251
which had all sorts of incentives

00:08:04.481 --> 00:08:06.791
encouraging people to become landlords.

00:08:07.711 --> 00:08:09.741
After all, the bank would only

00:08:09.741 --> 00:08:12.541
require a small deposit, a tenant’s

00:08:12.581 --> 00:08:14.761
monthly rent would more than cover

00:08:14.981 --> 00:08:16.881
the monthly mortgage costs, and

00:08:16.891 --> 00:08:18.861
the price would continue to rise.

00:08:20.201 --> 00:08:22.341
What this meant was that housing

00:08:22.611 --> 00:08:25.001
increasingly stopped being treated

00:08:25.311 --> 00:08:28.371
primarily as a place to live, and started

00:08:28.441 --> 00:08:30.951
being treated as a financial asset.

00:08:32.111 --> 00:08:34.001
Then, of course, came the

00:08:34.021 --> 00:08:37.111
Great Financial Crisis of 2008.

00:08:38.281 --> 00:08:41.261
This crisis, which began with risky

00:08:41.261 --> 00:08:42.811
mortgages in the United States,

00:08:43.161 --> 00:08:45.081
showed what could happen when

00:08:45.091 --> 00:08:47.191
housing prices became completely

00:08:47.201 --> 00:08:49.901
disconnected from economic fundamentals.

00:08:50.781 --> 00:08:52.671
As you'll know, when the bubble

00:08:52.707 --> 00:08:55.191
burst, millions of people lost their

00:08:55.201 --> 00:08:57.731
homes, banks collapsed, and the

00:08:57.731 --> 00:09:00.111
global economy went into freefall.

00:09:01.121 --> 00:09:02.667
You might think this would

00:09:02.667 --> 00:09:03.931
have taught everyone a lesson.

00:09:04.231 --> 00:09:05.461
That it might have led to a

00:09:05.461 --> 00:09:07.461
complete rethink of housing

00:09:07.671 --> 00:09:08.991
as an investment vehicle.

00:09:09.591 --> 00:09:12.361
But what actually happened was,

00:09:12.811 --> 00:09:14.391
in many ways, the opposite.

00:09:15.211 --> 00:09:17.311
Governments and central banks were

00:09:17.341 --> 00:09:20.191
absolutely terrified of another collapse.

00:09:20.621 --> 00:09:22.991
So instead of allowing prices to

00:09:22.991 --> 00:09:25.291
fall to more affordable levels,

00:09:25.511 --> 00:09:27.201
they did everything in their power

00:09:27.451 --> 00:09:29.831
to support the market and prevent

00:09:29.861 --> 00:09:31.771
prices from dropping too far.

00:09:32.551 --> 00:09:34.811
They pumped lots of money into the

00:09:34.831 --> 00:09:37.801
financial system, and kept interest rates

00:09:37.941 --> 00:09:40.641
extremely low, for a very long time.

00:09:41.361 --> 00:09:43.501
In some countries, rates stayed

00:09:43.541 --> 00:09:46.101
close to zero for more than a decade.

00:09:47.057 --> 00:09:48.887
The aim was to make borrowing

00:09:48.897 --> 00:09:50.717
cheap, encourage spending,

00:09:51.017 --> 00:09:52.797
and keep economies alive.

00:09:53.457 --> 00:09:55.887
And in many ways, it worked.

00:09:56.187 --> 00:09:57.767
The world bounced back.

00:09:58.347 --> 00:10:00.487
But there was a side effect.

00:10:00.857 --> 00:10:04.027
A huge inflow of capital into assets:

00:10:04.327 --> 00:10:07.817
stocks, bonds, and crucially, property.

00:10:08.697 --> 00:10:10.857
And this is where the idea of

00:10:10.857 --> 00:10:13.787
housing as a global market starts

00:10:13.787 --> 00:10:15.337
to make a little more sense.

00:10:16.577 --> 00:10:19.167
In the past, the price of a home was

00:10:19.177 --> 00:10:21.967
mostly determined by local factors:

00:10:22.317 --> 00:10:24.837
local wages, local demand, local

00:10:24.837 --> 00:10:27.167
supply, because the people buying

00:10:27.297 --> 00:10:29.457
and living in them would be locals.

00:10:30.017 --> 00:10:33.367
But increasingly, housing prices were

00:10:33.367 --> 00:10:35.387
being influenced by global money.

00:10:35.757 --> 00:10:37.397
Money looking for safety.

00:10:37.817 --> 00:10:39.787
Money looking for returns.

00:10:40.977 --> 00:10:43.567
And this money isn’t abstract.

00:10:43.667 --> 00:10:46.157
It comes from pension funds, insurance

00:10:46.187 --> 00:10:49.077
companies, investment firms, and wealthy

00:10:49.077 --> 00:10:51.187
individuals, all looking for places

00:10:51.367 --> 00:10:54.217
to park large sums of money in assets

00:10:54.447 --> 00:10:57.337
that feel stable and predictable.

00:10:58.917 --> 00:11:01.907
Compared to complex financial products,

00:11:02.057 --> 00:11:05.087
housing looks reassuringly simple.

00:11:05.577 --> 00:11:06.847
It exists physically.

00:11:07.007 --> 00:11:09.117
It generates income through rent.

00:11:09.547 --> 00:11:12.007
And governments have a strong incentive

00:11:12.197 --> 00:11:13.877
to stop its value from collapsing.

00:11:14.877 --> 00:11:17.647
And once housing becomes part of

00:11:17.647 --> 00:11:19.727
that global flow of capital, it

00:11:19.727 --> 00:11:22.457
stops behaving like an ordinary good.

00:11:23.387 --> 00:11:24.967
At that point, it doesn’t really

00:11:24.967 --> 00:11:26.507
matter whether a flat is in

00:11:26.787 --> 00:11:29.167
London, Lisbon, or Toronto.

00:11:29.617 --> 00:11:31.357
What matters is that it’s in

00:11:31.357 --> 00:11:33.347
a country with a stable legal

00:11:33.347 --> 00:11:35.707
system, strong property rights,

00:11:35.877 --> 00:11:37.777
and a reputation for safety.

00:11:38.567 --> 00:11:41.347
That’s why similar patterns started

00:11:41.347 --> 00:11:43.537
to appear in very different places;

00:11:44.247 --> 00:11:47.537
a fireman in Paris was now no longer

00:11:47.547 --> 00:11:49.567
bidding for a property against the

00:11:49.567 --> 00:11:51.647
local greengrocer, schoolteacher,

00:11:51.827 --> 00:11:54.167
and wedding photographer, but against

00:11:54.177 --> 00:11:56.867
sophisticated international investors.

00:11:57.617 --> 00:12:00.797
So, demand for housing soon started to

00:12:00.797 --> 00:12:03.907
significantly outstrip supply in most

00:12:03.907 --> 00:12:06.717
major cities, further pushing up prices.

00:12:07.497 --> 00:12:09.647
Now, the obvious question is,

00:12:10.087 --> 00:12:12.857
“if demand is so high, why don't

00:12:12.857 --> 00:12:14.497
we just build more houses?”

00:12:15.587 --> 00:12:16.977
This is where we need to

00:12:16.977 --> 00:12:18.467
talk about housing supply.

00:12:19.117 --> 00:12:21.367
Because alongside all these

00:12:21.377 --> 00:12:23.577
financial factors pushing up

00:12:23.627 --> 00:12:26.427
prices, there's also been a chronic

00:12:26.477 --> 00:12:28.867
failure to build enough housing

00:12:29.107 --> 00:12:30.967
where people actually want to live.

00:12:32.217 --> 00:12:35.207
In the UK, the planning system is

00:12:35.207 --> 00:12:38.487
notoriously complex and restrictive.

00:12:38.937 --> 00:12:40.657
Getting permission to build can

00:12:40.657 --> 00:12:43.517
take years, and even when permission

00:12:43.527 --> 00:12:46.587
is granted, local opposition often

00:12:46.597 --> 00:12:49.337
delays or blocks development entirely.

00:12:50.287 --> 00:12:52.267
There's actually an acronym for this:

00:12:52.697 --> 00:12:55.557
NIMBY, which stands for "Not In My

00:12:55.567 --> 00:12:58.187
Back Yard", and describes someone

00:12:58.367 --> 00:13:00.427
who opposes new construction in

00:13:00.427 --> 00:13:03.157
their area, worried it will change

00:13:03.177 --> 00:13:04.467
the character of the neighbourhood

00:13:04.677 --> 00:13:07.157
or reduce their own property values.

00:13:08.407 --> 00:13:09.577
And then there are the

00:13:09.637 --> 00:13:10.977
practical constraints.

00:13:11.777 --> 00:13:14.777
You can't build more land in central

00:13:14.777 --> 00:13:17.727
London, or San Francisco, or Hong Kong.

00:13:18.297 --> 00:13:20.527
These cities are hemmed in by

00:13:20.577 --> 00:13:23.077
geography, and the most desirable

00:13:23.077 --> 00:13:25.007
areas are already built up.

00:13:26.007 --> 00:13:28.477
Add to this rising construction costs,

00:13:28.667 --> 00:13:31.177
labour shortages, and the fact that

00:13:31.187 --> 00:13:33.657
developers sometimes hold onto land

00:13:33.967 --> 00:13:35.917
rather than building on it—hoping

00:13:36.107 --> 00:13:38.497
values will increase even further—and

00:13:38.777 --> 00:13:41.047
you have a situation where supply

00:13:41.297 --> 00:13:43.727
simply can't keep up with demand.

00:13:44.507 --> 00:13:47.727
So even if the money side of things were

00:13:47.727 --> 00:13:50.387
sorted out, we'd still have a fundamental

00:13:50.387 --> 00:13:52.787
shortage of homes in the places

00:13:52.787 --> 00:13:54.647
where people actually want  to live.

00:13:55.927 --> 00:13:58.587
And demand keeps growing.

00:13:58.947 --> 00:14:00.907
Not just from population growth,

00:14:01.087 --> 00:14:03.277
but from changing demographics.

00:14:03.717 --> 00:14:05.437
People are living longer.

00:14:05.897 --> 00:14:07.797
More people are living alone.

00:14:08.977 --> 00:14:10.687
In much of the developed world,

00:14:10.927 --> 00:14:13.377
the average household size has been

00:14:13.377 --> 00:14:15.657
shrinking for decades, which means

00:14:15.947 --> 00:14:17.957
you need more units of housing

00:14:18.247 --> 00:14:19.557
for the same number of people.

00:14:20.350 --> 00:14:22.618
Add to this an increasing number

00:14:22.618 --> 00:14:24.668
of people, both domestically and

00:14:24.688 --> 00:14:26.668
internationally, migrating into

00:14:26.668 --> 00:14:29.248
cities, and you have even more

00:14:29.248 --> 00:14:31.098
pressure on the housing supply.

00:14:32.428 --> 00:14:34.508
All these factors mean that even

00:14:34.518 --> 00:14:36.778
maintaining current affordability

00:14:36.788 --> 00:14:38.788
would require building significantly

00:14:38.818 --> 00:14:40.768
more homes than we currently do.

00:14:41.498 --> 00:14:45.208
So, prices are almost guaranteed to rise.

00:14:46.078 --> 00:14:49.638
This isn’t just speculation or financial

00:14:49.658 --> 00:14:52.238
engineering, it’s basic arithmetic.

00:14:52.638 --> 00:14:54.938
More people competing for the same

00:14:54.938 --> 00:14:58.448
number of homes pushes up both rents and

00:14:58.468 --> 00:15:01.538
prices, regardless of how sensible or

00:15:01.648 --> 00:15:04.048
well-intentioned housing policy might be.

00:15:05.178 --> 00:15:06.338
And there is more.

00:15:06.818 --> 00:15:08.368
Just when it seemed like low

00:15:08.368 --> 00:15:09.838
interest rates might last

00:15:09.838 --> 00:15:12.108
forever, everything changed again.

00:15:12.978 --> 00:15:16.268
In 2022, inflation came roaring back.

00:15:16.778 --> 00:15:19.098
Central banks, which had spent over

00:15:19.098 --> 00:15:21.548
a decade keeping rates at historic

00:15:21.558 --> 00:15:24.358
lows, suddenly had to do a u-turn.

00:15:25.168 --> 00:15:27.218
In a matter of months, interest

00:15:27.218 --> 00:15:29.968
rates went from near zero to

00:15:29.968 --> 00:15:32.158
levels not seen in over a decade.

00:15:33.238 --> 00:15:35.318
In the UK, the base rate

00:15:35.468 --> 00:15:39.018
went from 0.1% to 5%.

00:15:39.688 --> 00:15:40.688
In the United States,

00:15:40.978 --> 00:15:43.038
rates rose even faster.

00:15:43.858 --> 00:15:44.838
For anyone with a

00:15:44.838 --> 00:15:47.238
mortgage, this was a shock.

00:15:47.708 --> 00:15:49.278
If your rate wasn’t fixed,

00:15:49.528 --> 00:15:51.448
your monthly payments soared.

00:15:52.098 --> 00:15:53.508
People who had borrowed the

00:15:53.518 --> 00:15:55.598
maximum amount when rates were

00:15:55.925 --> 00:15:58.538
2% suddenly found themselves

00:15:58.538 --> 00:16:00.628
paying twice as much each month.

00:16:01.618 --> 00:16:03.228
You might have thought this would

00:16:03.228 --> 00:16:05.868
have led to a fall in house prices,

00:16:06.068 --> 00:16:07.858
as people wouldn’t have been

00:16:07.858 --> 00:16:09.498
able to borrow as much as before.

00:16:10.108 --> 00:16:12.548
But here's the thing: house

00:16:12.548 --> 00:16:14.368
prices didn't collapse.

00:16:14.898 --> 00:16:17.678
They did fall slightly in some areas,

00:16:17.828 --> 00:16:20.258
and sales slowed down dramatically.

00:16:20.878 --> 00:16:23.978
But prices remained stubbornly high.

00:16:25.038 --> 00:16:25.498
Why?

00:16:26.088 --> 00:16:28.348
Well, because many people who already

00:16:28.408 --> 00:16:30.718
owned homes simply stayed put.

00:16:31.658 --> 00:16:33.318
If you had a cheap mortgage

00:16:33.558 --> 00:16:36.238
locked in, selling rarely made

00:16:36.238 --> 00:16:38.458
sense — because wherever you moved

00:16:38.468 --> 00:16:40.888
next would almost certainly come

00:16:40.888 --> 00:16:42.598
with a much more expensive loan.

00:16:43.848 --> 00:16:46.608
This created a kind of gridlock.

00:16:46.998 --> 00:16:49.488
Not enough homes for sale, still too

00:16:49.488 --> 00:16:51.238
expensive for first-time buyers to

00:16:51.238 --> 00:16:54.538
afford, but with even higher monthly

00:16:54.538 --> 00:16:56.838
costs due to expensive mortgages.

00:16:57.608 --> 00:16:59.148
In other words, the problem

00:16:59.318 --> 00:17:01.008
got worse, not better.

00:17:02.098 --> 00:17:05.228
So by this point, housing is being

00:17:05.318 --> 00:17:08.128
pulled in several directions at once:

00:17:08.738 --> 00:17:11.998
cheap money pushing prices up, global

00:17:11.998 --> 00:17:15.368
capital treating homes as assets, more

00:17:15.368 --> 00:17:17.848
people competing for housing in the same

00:17:17.858 --> 00:17:21.238
cities, and a system that struggles to

00:17:21.248 --> 00:17:23.458
build enough homes where they’re needed.

00:17:24.658 --> 00:17:28.268
And these are often exacerbated, made

00:17:28.268 --> 00:17:31.208
worse, by specific local conditions,

00:17:31.458 --> 00:17:33.758
so let’s talk about some of those now.

00:17:34.618 --> 00:17:37.228
Particularly in Europe, and in almost

00:17:37.268 --> 00:17:41.268
any reasonably sized city, an oft-cited

00:17:41.398 --> 00:17:44.958
culprit is short-term rentals, and one

00:17:44.958 --> 00:17:47.698
name in particular coming to mind: Airbnb.

00:17:48.898 --> 00:17:51.918
Landlords were choosing not to rent out

00:17:51.918 --> 00:17:54.198
their apartments long-term to locals,

00:17:54.318 --> 00:17:57.468
but to tourists on a short-term basis.

00:17:58.448 --> 00:18:00.798
The economic rationale for this

00:18:01.158 --> 00:18:03.458
is pretty obvious; a landlord can

00:18:03.458 --> 00:18:05.488
typically make much more money.

00:18:06.158 --> 00:18:08.708
But the effect on the local property

00:18:08.708 --> 00:18:11.528
market, as no doubt many of you will

00:18:11.528 --> 00:18:14.048
know all too well, is that it has

00:18:14.048 --> 00:18:16.398
reduced the supply of available housing

00:18:16.638 --> 00:18:19.228
for locals and significantly pushed

00:18:19.268 --> 00:18:22.998
up prices, both to buy and to rent.

00:18:24.138 --> 00:18:27.018
In Madrid and Barcelona, for example,

00:18:27.168 --> 00:18:30.018
over the past decade, rents have risen

00:18:30.258 --> 00:18:34.798
by an average of 60% and prices by 90%.

00:18:35.748 --> 00:18:37.668
And then there are the countries

00:18:37.848 --> 00:18:40.178
which courted wealthy foreigners with

00:18:40.188 --> 00:18:42.908
citizenship or tax incentives on the

00:18:42.908 --> 00:18:45.198
condition that they invested in property.

00:18:45.908 --> 00:18:49.378
In Malta, the tiny Mediterranean island

00:18:49.558 --> 00:18:52.168
where I used to live, citizenship was

00:18:52.188 --> 00:18:54.118
given to foreigners on the condition

00:18:54.324 --> 00:18:56.474
they bought property over a certain

00:18:56.474 --> 00:18:59.094
value, thereby reducing the housing

00:18:59.094 --> 00:19:02.074
supply for locals and pushing up prices

00:19:02.844 --> 00:19:05.254
. On the other side of Europe, Portugal

00:19:05.514 --> 00:19:07.794
had a similar scheme which offered

00:19:07.804 --> 00:19:09.814
residency to people investing

00:19:09.954 --> 00:19:11.404
in the local property market.

00:19:12.434 --> 00:19:15.434
In both of these cases, these policies

00:19:15.704 --> 00:19:18.014
successfully attracted lots of foreign

00:19:18.014 --> 00:19:19.644
money that would otherwise not have

00:19:19.654 --> 00:19:22.714
come, but it also helped push up

00:19:22.714 --> 00:19:25.324
prices to unprecedented levels.

00:19:26.394 --> 00:19:29.174
In Malta, property prices have

00:19:29.254 --> 00:19:31.044
doubled in the past decade.

00:19:31.594 --> 00:19:33.094
The average asking price in

00:19:33.094 --> 00:19:37.174
Malta is €414,000, yet the

00:19:37.174 --> 00:19:40.224
average salary is under €25,000.

00:19:41.144 --> 00:19:44.074
And it’s a similar situation in Portugal.

00:19:45.204 --> 00:19:47.414
In places like this, home ownership

00:19:47.424 --> 00:19:49.704
for anyone without family help

00:19:49.954 --> 00:19:51.924
is now something of a pipe dream.

00:19:53.144 --> 00:19:55.444
And this brings us to one of the

00:19:55.444 --> 00:19:58.484
most insidious effects: housing

00:19:58.484 --> 00:20:00.624
wealth is becoming hereditary.

00:20:01.924 --> 00:20:04.694
Increasingly, the only way young people

00:20:04.704 --> 00:20:07.214
can afford to buy is with help from

00:20:07.214 --> 00:20:10.134
parents - money for a deposit, co-signing

00:20:10.134 --> 00:20:12.834
mortgages, sometimes buying outright.

00:20:13.614 --> 00:20:15.414
If your parents own property,

00:20:15.834 --> 00:20:17.344
you might still get on the

00:20:17.344 --> 00:20:19.214
ladder, as the expression goes.

00:20:20.004 --> 00:20:21.894
If they don't, you're locked out,

00:20:22.254 --> 00:20:24.194
regardless of how hard you work.

00:20:25.054 --> 00:20:28.204
It means your ability to own a home

00:20:28.474 --> 00:20:31.414
depends less on your income than on

00:20:31.414 --> 00:20:33.154
whether you were lucky enough to have

00:20:33.184 --> 00:20:35.154
parents who bought property decades

00:20:35.154 --> 00:20:36.994
ago when it was still affordable.

00:20:38.084 --> 00:20:40.774
So this is the picture so far.

00:20:41.154 --> 00:20:44.254
Global forces push prices up everywhere.

00:20:44.684 --> 00:20:46.684
Local factors make the problem

00:20:46.684 --> 00:20:48.414
worse in certain places.

00:20:49.134 --> 00:20:52.494
And once prices reach a certain level,

00:20:52.864 --> 00:20:55.404
you get the situation that exists in many

00:20:55.404 --> 00:20:58.044
towns and cities all over the world today.

00:20:58.764 --> 00:21:02.024
Whether it’s paying sky-high rent or not

00:21:02.034 --> 00:21:04.164
being able to afford a deposit for your

00:21:04.164 --> 00:21:07.414
first home, just having your own roof over

00:21:07.414 --> 00:21:10.064
your head is more expensive than ever.

00:21:11.064 --> 00:21:13.544
So, this brings us to the

00:21:13.584 --> 00:21:14.974
trickiest part of the story.

00:21:15.634 --> 00:21:18.858
What, if anything can be done about it?

00:21:19.804 --> 00:21:21.714
It’s a problem that lots of people

00:21:21.724 --> 00:21:24.034
like to see easy solutions to.

00:21:24.614 --> 00:21:27.614
Build more homes, control rents, tax

00:21:27.644 --> 00:21:30.554
speculation, restrict short-term rentals,

00:21:30.774 --> 00:21:33.554
and stop prices from rising so fast.

00:21:34.934 --> 00:21:37.804
The reality is that all of these solutions

00:21:38.194 --> 00:21:40.394
come with their own share of problems.

00:21:40.964 --> 00:21:44.134
Building takes time, and in many

00:21:44.134 --> 00:21:46.904
countries–especially in the UK–it

00:21:47.264 --> 00:21:49.064
is fraught with regulations.

00:21:49.724 --> 00:21:52.374
Removing planning constraints sounds

00:21:52.604 --> 00:21:55.734
simple, but in practice it rarely is.

00:21:56.474 --> 00:21:58.134
Rent control is one of the

00:21:58.134 --> 00:21:59.904
most debated solutions.

00:22:00.584 --> 00:22:04.714
The idea is simple: cap how much landlords

00:22:04.714 --> 00:22:06.904
can increase rent each year, making

00:22:06.904 --> 00:22:09.084
housing more affordable for tenants.

00:22:09.924 --> 00:22:12.994
But in practice, it's complicated.

00:22:13.594 --> 00:22:16.284
Economists often point to cities like

00:22:16.464 --> 00:22:19.444
San Francisco or Stockholm, where strict

00:22:19.464 --> 00:22:22.654
rent control led to some landlords taking

00:22:22.654 --> 00:22:24.824
properties off the rental market entirely,

00:22:25.114 --> 00:22:27.364
either selling them or leaving them empty.

00:22:28.514 --> 00:22:31.974
This creates a paradox: by trying to make

00:22:31.974 --> 00:22:35.334
rent cheaper for some, it often makes it

00:22:35.384 --> 00:22:37.962
harder for others to find a home at all.

00:22:39.184 --> 00:22:41.634
That said, some cities have

00:22:41.634 --> 00:22:43.454
found some middle ground.

00:22:43.864 --> 00:22:46.754
Berlin tried strict rent controls,

00:22:46.904 --> 00:22:48.604
had to partially reverse them,

00:22:48.934 --> 00:22:50.974
but maintained some protections.

00:22:51.514 --> 00:22:53.764
The key seems to be balancing

00:22:53.834 --> 00:22:56.024
tenant protection with incentives

00:22:56.024 --> 00:22:57.828
to keep landlords in the market.

00:22:58.324 --> 00:23:00.194
It's not a silver bullet, but

00:23:00.414 --> 00:23:02.214
it's not entirely useless either.

00:23:03.364 --> 00:23:05.484
Restricting short-term rentals is

00:23:05.484 --> 00:23:07.954
something many cities have now started

00:23:07.974 --> 00:23:11.674
to do, with some success, but there are

00:23:11.674 --> 00:23:13.764
question marks about how deep an effect

00:23:13.784 --> 00:23:15.904
this will have on revenue from tourism.

00:23:16.934 --> 00:23:19.454
Taxing speculation is a nice idea

00:23:19.454 --> 00:23:22.204
in theory, but it quickly comes up

00:23:22.364 --> 00:23:24.874
against another uncomfortable reality:

00:23:25.784 --> 00:23:28.314
homeowners, who in many countries

00:23:28.484 --> 00:23:30.654
make up a majority of the voting

00:23:30.654 --> 00:23:33.274
population, have a vested interest

00:23:33.464 --> 00:23:36.894
in prices not coming down, especially

00:23:37.094 --> 00:23:39.354
if they took on a large mortgage.

00:23:40.464 --> 00:23:42.354
For millions of people, their

00:23:42.364 --> 00:23:44.724
home isn’t just somewhere to live.

00:23:45.274 --> 00:23:46.668
It’s their main asset.

00:23:47.004 --> 00:23:48.864
A large part of their retirement plan.

00:23:49.374 --> 00:23:50.814
Their financial safety net.

00:23:51.714 --> 00:23:55.564
So when house prices rise, homeowners

00:23:55.864 --> 00:23:58.214
feel richer and more secure.

00:23:58.944 --> 00:24:01.674
But when prices fall — or even stop

00:24:01.694 --> 00:24:05.224
rising — the same group feels threatened.

00:24:06.024 --> 00:24:08.364
So, governments face a dilemma.

00:24:09.074 --> 00:24:11.624
On the one hand, high house prices

00:24:11.904 --> 00:24:14.004
lock younger people out of home

00:24:14.004 --> 00:24:16.144
ownership, increase inequality,

00:24:16.394 --> 00:24:18.164
and put pressure on rents.

00:24:19.004 --> 00:24:21.504
On the other hand, falling house prices

00:24:21.714 --> 00:24:24.444
risk angering existing homeowners and

00:24:24.444 --> 00:24:27.034
losing voters, destabilising banks,

00:24:27.424 --> 00:24:30.084
and triggering wider economic problems.

00:24:30.854 --> 00:24:34.244
So instead of dramatic reform, what

00:24:34.244 --> 00:24:37.194
we often see are small, cautious

00:24:37.254 --> 00:24:39.544
adjustments, adjustments that don’t

00:24:39.604 --> 00:24:42.224
always have the intended consequences.

00:24:42.854 --> 00:24:45.274
Governments announce ambitious plans

00:24:45.484 --> 00:24:47.664
to build more homes, like the new

00:24:47.664 --> 00:24:49.254
Labour government did in the UK,

00:24:49.614 --> 00:24:52.214
but planning slows down everything,

00:24:52.504 --> 00:24:54.944
and they quickly miss their targets.

00:24:55.444 --> 00:24:57.174
They launch initiatives to help

00:24:57.184 --> 00:24:59.274
first-time buyers with interest-free

00:24:59.274 --> 00:25:02.224
loans, but these often end up pushing

00:25:02.224 --> 00:25:04.634
prices higher by increasing demand.

00:25:05.214 --> 00:25:07.414
They talk about controlling rents, but

00:25:07.774 --> 00:25:09.784
make promises to potential investors

00:25:10.014 --> 00:25:12.054
that their rights will also be protected.

00:25:12.614 --> 00:25:14.394
They make pledges to crack down on

00:25:14.424 --> 00:25:17.604
Airbnb, but all that happens is the

00:25:17.604 --> 00:25:20.334
implementation of token "tourist taxes".

00:25:21.544 --> 00:25:23.664
And then there’s the issue of timing.

00:25:24.624 --> 00:25:27.704
Even if a government decides today to

00:25:27.704 --> 00:25:30.014
build significantly more housing, the

00:25:30.014 --> 00:25:32.534
effects won’t be felt for several years.

00:25:33.064 --> 00:25:35.134
Planning, the actual construction,

00:25:35.524 --> 00:25:36.514
building in places where

00:25:36.514 --> 00:25:37.974
people actually want to live.

00:25:38.464 --> 00:25:39.974
That all takes time.

00:25:40.874 --> 00:25:43.114
So where does that leave us?

00:25:43.654 --> 00:25:45.734
Can house prices keep rising

00:25:45.734 --> 00:25:47.654
faster than incomes indefinitely?

00:25:48.504 --> 00:25:51.044
The optimistic view is that they can't.

00:25:51.454 --> 00:25:54.714
At some point, prices must correct,

00:25:55.094 --> 00:25:57.134
either through a crash or through

00:25:57.134 --> 00:25:58.744
a long period of stagnation

00:25:58.954 --> 00:26:01.244
while wages gradually catch up.

00:26:02.074 --> 00:26:04.714
The pessimistic view is that we're not

00:26:04.744 --> 00:26:07.364
in a traditional bubble waiting to pop.

00:26:08.154 --> 00:26:11.644
This is, as they say, a new equilibrium.

00:26:12.324 --> 00:26:14.504
As long as housing is seen as one of

00:26:14.504 --> 00:26:17.244
the safest places to park wealth, as

00:26:17.244 --> 00:26:19.194
long as there's more capital looking

00:26:19.194 --> 00:26:21.244
for safe returns than there are good

00:26:21.284 --> 00:26:23.414
investment opportunities, as long

00:26:23.414 --> 00:26:25.594
as people continue to move to towns

00:26:25.594 --> 00:26:28.114
and cities, and as long as we don't

00:26:28.154 --> 00:26:30.154
build enough homes in desirable

00:26:30.154 --> 00:26:33.224
locations, prices will keep climbing.

00:26:34.244 --> 00:26:36.754
The truth is probably somewhere in

00:26:36.754 --> 00:26:39.374
between, and will vary by location.

00:26:39.844 --> 00:26:42.054
Some markets may see corrections.

00:26:42.444 --> 00:26:43.964
Others may plateau, or

00:26:43.964 --> 00:26:45.324
even continue to rise.

00:26:46.154 --> 00:26:48.234
Unfortunately, it seems that the

00:26:48.244 --> 00:26:50.714
fundamental tension between housing

00:26:51.004 --> 00:26:53.964
as a human necessity and housing as

00:26:53.964 --> 00:26:56.624
a financial asset is here to stay.

00:26:58.044 --> 00:27:00.314
OK, then, that is it for today's

00:27:00.334 --> 00:27:03.204
episode on the global property crisis.

00:27:03.534 --> 00:27:05.144
As always, I would love to know

00:27:05.144 --> 00:27:06.614
what you thought of this episode.

00:27:06.934 --> 00:27:08.284
How have property prices

00:27:08.284 --> 00:27:09.734
changed in your city?

00:27:10.084 --> 00:27:12.964
How has this affected your life, and

00:27:12.964 --> 00:27:15.174
what do you think can be done about it?

00:27:15.464 --> 00:27:17.294
For the members among you, you can head

00:27:17.294 --> 00:27:19.334
right into our community forum, which is

00:27:19.334 --> 00:27:22.184
at community.leonardoenglish.com and get

00:27:22.184 --> 00:27:24.334
chatting away to other curious minds.

00:27:24.854 --> 00:27:26.564
You've been listening to English Learning

00:27:26.564 --> 00:27:29.154
for Curious Minds by Leonardo English.

00:27:29.454 --> 00:27:32.194
I'm Alastair Budge, you stay safe, and

00:27:32.194 --> 00:27:34.294
I'll catch you in the next episode.

